title: Psychology Study Group, Task 3 Auto - Function of Behavior
authors: EDUC 3100 Assessment Module

~~~~

Introduction [id=fba2_intro_section]
------------

::fba2_introduction [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Introduction"]

Annie: Okay, so... remember how I told my roommate to try the sticker chart? It works — he goes to his room now, toys before bed, all of that. But the second she says "time for bed," he takes off running and laughing. Every single time. She thinks I made it worse. [face=concerned]

JJ: Running? Like, around the house? [face=awe]

Annie: Through the house, behind the couch, under the dining table. At first she'd just call his name from the doorway. Now she's literally sprinting after him. He knocked a lamp off the end table last week. [face=fear]

JJ: Sounds like he's trying to get a reaction out of her. Classic attention-seeking, right? [face=explaining]

Annie: Maybe? One night she tried not reacting — just stayed in the kitchen, didn't chase. He got wilder and wilder until she gave in and went after him. Now she's resorted to bribing — she promised him extra screen time last night just to get him to stop. He eventually wears himself out, but she texted me afterward and just said, "I want this to be over." [face=concerned]

Lin: Hmm. Let's not jump to conclusions about why he's doing it — not yet. But it does sound like whatever's happening, the current approach isn't working. [face=serious]

JJ: I mean, it seems pretty simple. If he runs, no toys the next night. He'll learn fast. [face=explaining]

Annie: That feels harsh. He's six. [face=concerned]

Lin: And we don't even know why he's running yet. If we pick the wrong consequence, we could make it worse. [face=serious]

Function of Behavior [id=fba2_function_intro]
---------------------

Lin: This is actually exactly what they warned us about in class. You can't just pick a consequence and hope — the intervention has to address the function of the behavior. [face=serious]

Annie: The function? Like... what the behavior does? [face=hectic]

JJ: Oh! I think I sort of remember this. It's why the kid is doing it — like I said, Johnny's probably doing it for the attention.

Lin: That's the right idea — function is about why the behavior keeps happening. But let's not assume we already know Johnny's. I remember Lianne telling us it's better to try to actively recall something than to just passively look it up. You understand it better that way.

JJ: Okay, fair. I think I can write a prompt to get AI to check our answer, at least. That way we'll know if we're on the right track. [face=explaining]

::fba2_ai_function_def [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Define Function of Behavior"]

--- wait @fba2_ai_function_response.value ---

Annie: JJ thinks it's attention. What's your guess? [face=smile]

::
