  <Markdown>Maybe...</Markdown>
  <Distractor> Attention            </Distractor>
         <Key> Escape               </Key>
  <Distractor> Access to tangibles  </Distractor>
  <Distractor> Sensory              </Distractor>
</ChoiceInput>
::

--- wait @fba2_johnny_function_prediction_inline ---

Annie: Okay — so we need to figure out WHY Johnny is running away at bedtime. [face=smile]

JJ: Right, and I still think it's attention. He's laughing, she's chasing — that's a social interaction he's creating. [face=explaining]

Introducing Function of Behavior [id=fba2_function_concepts]
---------------------------------

Lin: Here are my notes from class. Based on what we covered, the four main functions of behavior are attention, escape, access to preferred activity or object, and sensory.

::fba2_function_notes [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Lin's Notes"]

JJ: And my notes say the function always refers to a type of reinforcement — positive or negative. Wait, that's key, right? It's always reinforcement, never punishment?

Annie: Positive and negative reinforcement! We went over that last time. I remember the gist, but I'm a little fuzzy on the details...

Lin: I took a picture of some examples our TA Lianne wrote on the board. Let me pull those up.

Review of Previously Learned Concepts [id=fba2_reinforcement_review_section]
--------------------------------------

Lin: Before we go further, let's make sure we actually remember the basics. Let's work through a few of these until we get, say, 3 in a row right. [face=serious]

JJ: Good call. Otherwise we might just be fooling ourselves! [face=smile]

::fba2_reinforcement_review [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Review Reinforcement Concepts"]

--- wait @fba2_reinforcement_mastery.completed ---

Teaching Function of Behavior [id=fba2_function_teaching]
------------------------------

JJ: Okay, I definitely needed that refresher. Some of those were trickier than I expected. [face=concerned]

Annie: I keep thinking about the screen time bribe. My roommate added something Johnny wanted — that's positive reinforcement, right? But it reinforced *her giving in*, not anything good about bedtime. [face=concerned]

Lin: Exactly — and that's why we need to understand function before we intervene. Lianne also mentioned something else in class — she said that if the function is attention or tangibles, it usually involves positive reinforcement. If the function is escape, it typically involves negative reinforcement. And for sensory, it can be either one.

Annie: My brain would really benefit from seeing all of that in one place. Like a chart or something. I bet AI could help with that.

JJ: Actually, I already tried this. My first prompt generated a chart where every cell had an example — but some of those combinations don't exist. The AI just made up plausible-sounding examples to fill every cell. I had to explicitly tell it which cells to leave blank. [face=explaining]

::fba2_ai_function_chart [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Create Function Chart with AI"]

--- wait @fba2_ai_chart_response.value ---

JJ: Two cells are blank! Escape involves removing something aversive, so it doesn't combine with positive reinforcement. And tangibles are about gaining something, so they don't combine with negative reinforcement. [face=explaining]

Your Turn: Own Examples [id=fba2_own_examples_section]
------------------------

Annie: We won't learn this just by reading it. Let's each come up with our own examples for each function. [face=smile]

Lin: Right. For each function, try to think of a situation involving positive reinforcement, and another involving negative reinforcement. Some of those combinations are going to be tricky — that's the point.

